<DOC><DOCNO> AP880823-0252 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 2004EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-Revco     08-23 0239</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Revco,0247</SECOND><HEAD>Bankruptcy Judge Approves Revco Credit Arrangement</HEAD><DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal bankruptcy judge Tuesday approved a$145 million credit plan for Revco D.S. Inc., a drugstore chainthat sought protection from its creditors in court last month.   ``We interpret this new credit facility as a strong vote ofconfidence from our senior bank lenders and the court,'' said RevcoChairman Boake A. Sells. ``Our stores are open. We have beensaying, `Revco is in business to stay.' We believe our banks aresaying the same thing.''   Under the agreement approved by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Harold F.White, Wells Fargo Bank and Marine Midland Bank will be the leadlenders extending the credit to Revco through Feb. 1, 1990.   The new arrangement is expected to be finalized Sept. 8, Revcosaid, and will replace a $50 million interim financing agreement byWells Fargo and Marine Midland since Aug. 3.   Revco filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection on July 28,about a month after it failed to make an interest payment on about$700 million in outstanding high-risk junk bonds used to financeits 1986 $1.5 billion leveraged buyout.   In a leveraged buyout a company is acquired largely throughborrowed funds repaid from a target company's profits or assetsales.   The Twinsburg, Ohio-based company sought protection fromcreditors after talks with bondholders broke down, becoming thelargest company involved in a leveraged buyout to take such action.</TEXT></DOC>